<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colliander Withdraws From NYD Leadership Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Colliander Withdraws From NYD Leadership Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2406103694 Stockholm SVENSKA DAGBLADET in Swedish 23 Jun 
94 p 11 </F>

<F P=103> PM2406103694 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm SVENSKA DAGBLADET </F>
<F P=105>  Swedish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hans O. Alfredsson: "Colliander Leaving </F>
Politics"] 
  [Excerpt] Vivianne Franzen can now lead New Democracy 
[NYD] unchallenged in the run-up to the election. Harriet 
Colliander is withdrawing, but she still thinks that she is the 
right and real party leader and that her party executive is the 
right and real party executive. 
  Her resignation is the result of the ballot among members 
that has been held since the extraordinary party congress. The 
votes were counted on Tuesday [21 June]. It emerged that 
Vivianne Franzen and her executive have the support of about 80 
percent of those who took part in the ballot. 
  Given that this is the situation Harriet Colliander has 
decided to give up. She is resigning as chairman of the party 
executive that was elected at the regular party congress in 
early April and will leave politics. She will not participate 
in the election campaign and she will not run for the Riksdag 
this fall. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-44230 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu124_o_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Northern Envoy: EU Decision `Unfortunate' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Northern Envoy: EU Decision `Unfortunate' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806100994 Nicosia Bayrak Radio in Turkish 1930 GMT 27 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2806100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Bayrak Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It has been reported that the decision on Cyprus 
taken at the European Union's [EU] Corfu summit has given the 
green light to full EU membership for south Cyprus and Malta. 
Osman Ertug, Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus' New York 
envoy, described the development as an unfortunate decision and 
said that it will not help the negotiation process on the island. 
  In his statement to Anatolia Agency, Ertug pointed out that 
the decision will deepen the rift in Cyprus and added: With 
this decision, the EU leaves us no alternatives but to merge 
with Turkey. If south Cyprus merges with the EU, then we have no 
options but to integrate with Turkey. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

