<H3> <TI>   Bonn Support for Dehaene Waning </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn Support for Dehaene Waning </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706140794 Hamburg DPA in German 1300 GMT 27 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2706140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- Following the failure to choose a 
successor for European Union Commission President Jacques 
Delors, the Federal Government is obviously distancing itself to 
a certain extent from its previous support of Belgian Prime 
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene. One must look for a solution over 
the next three weeks until the special summit in Brussels on 15 
July, Government Spokesman Dieter Vogel told the press on Monday 
[27 June]. One cannot yet see what the solution could be like. 
In a newspaper interview Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free 
Democratic Party), however, had praised Dehaene once again as a 
"dedicated European" and added that the European Union needs "a 
doer." Dehaene had failed to be chosen because of the British 
veto at the Corfu summit. 

</TEXT>

