<H3> <TI>   Government, Cuba Sign Maritime Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government, Cuba Sign Maritime Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206124194 Hamburg DPA in German 1030 GMT 22 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2206124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- A maritime agreement has been 
concluded between Cuba and Germany, which replaces a treaty 
between the former GDR and the Caribbean island. As the 
Transportation Ministry in Bonn announced on Wednesday [22 June] 
after negotiations with Havanna were concluded, the new 
agreement regulates, among other things, the freedom of 
establishment and the free transfer of cargo for maritime 
shipping. An important part of the agreement is the fact that 
ships of the partners to the agreement are treated like the 
respective country's own ships regarding access to ports and the 
use of services. In addition, the freedom of establishment is 
ensured for shiping companies. 

</TEXT>

