<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inflation Below 4 Percent for First Time in 25 Years </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inflation Below 4 Percent for First Time in 25 Years </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2206105094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1213 GMT 21 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2206105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Inflation Drops Below 4 Percent"] </F>
  [Excerpts] (ANSA) Rome, June 21 -- Inflation rates in eight 
major cities fell in June to an average of 3.7-3.8 percent, 
according to provisional figures released Tuesday [21 June] by 
the statistics institute Istat [Central Statistics Institute]. 
  This is the first time in 25 years that the average rate has 
fallen below 4 percent. 
  Food prices bucked the trend, rising higher than the average 
in June while clothing prices remained stable and electricity 
and heating costs varied greatly, falling in Bologna, Milan, 
Florence and Trieste but rising in Venice, Genoa and Naples. 
[passage omitted] 
  Premier Silvio Berlusconi and Labour Minister Clemente 
Mastella were amongst those who welcomed the low inflation 
figures after they were announced on Tuesday. "I hope this news 
does the markets good," said Berlusconi, "but often money 
markets have a logic all of their own, which is frequently far 
from reality." 
  For Mastella, the inflation figures could have positive 
repercussions for the labour market: "I hope these figures help. 
Falling consumer prices make it possible to proceed rapidly in 
the contract negotiation field." 
  Unionists, who met with government ministers for cost of 
labour talks this morning, saw the latest provisional inflation 
figures as a sign that a mini-budget promised by Treasury 
Minister Lamberto Dini yesterday would not be necessary. 
  "The fall in inflation shows that no corrective measures are 
necessary," said Sergio Cofferati of the CGIL [Italian General 
Confederation of Labor] union. "These conditions are right for 
reducing interest rates and thus keep the borrowing requirement 
under control." 

</TEXT>

