<H3> <TI>   Italy's Berlusconi: Other EU Candidates Needed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Italy's Berlusconi: Other EU Candidates Needed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2706103194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1227 GMT 25 
Jun 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2706103194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Commission, No </F>
Replacement for Delors as Summit Ends"] 
  [Excerpts] (ANSA) Corfu, June 25 -- The European Summit 
concluded today without reaching agreement on a successor to 
European Commission president Jacques Delors, who leaves his 
post at the end of the year. [passage omitted] 
  In a comment earlier this morning, before meetings began on 
the second day of the summit, Italian Prime Minister Silvio 
Berlusconi said that "if there is no agreement today on one of 
the present candidates, others must be sought." 
  During negotiations yesterday, Italy had been seen as the 
swing vote in an election that confronted "pro-Europe" forces 
(which the Belgian Dehaene would be expected to represent) and 
the so-called Euro-skeptics, led by the British. 
  Italy, Martino explained, had "placed no personal or 
ideological vetos, just a methodological one" he said, referring 
to earlier reluctance to approve Dehaene as the result of 
Italy's "perplexity" because "a Franco-German initiative had 
been set in motion without prior consultation." 
  The Italian Foreign Minister said that Britain's position 
was 
different, however. "The problem is a methodological one and 
Prime Minister Major says he's not ready to bargain on the 
issue." 
  The question had seemed near to resolution late last night 
and early this morning, with much attention focusing on how 
Italian opinion would swing. 
  The new government of Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, 
which 
has presented itself as more "Euro-moderate" than previous 
administrations, was seen by some as forging a conservative, 
"Euro-skeptic" alliance with Britain. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

