<H3> <TI>   Chemical Weapons Group To Meet 27 Jun-1 Jul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chemical Weapons Group To Meet 27 Jun-1 Jul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2706143094 London REUTER Textline Database in English 27 
Jun 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2706143094 </F>
<F P=104>  London REUTER Textline Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article from Brussels EUROPE: "Commission for </F>
Prohibition of Chemical Weapons To Convene in The Hague"] 
  [Text] The Preparatory Commission for the Organisation for 
the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) will hold its seventh 
plenary session from 27 June to 1 July in The Hague. It is 
expected to be attended by a majority of the representatives of 
the 157 states which have signed the Convention on Chemical 
Weapons. The session will be chaired by Ambassador Grigoriy 
Berdenikov of the Russian Federation. The Convention on 
Chemical Weapons, opened to signature on 13 January 1993 and 
signed by 157 states, will enter into force 180 days after the 
date of deposit of the 65th instrument of ratification, but in 
no case earlier than two years after its opening for signature. 
Eight countries have ratified the convention so far. As soon 
as it enters into force, the convention will be applied by the 
OPCW. All major decisions are taken in its plenary sessions, 
and work is prepared in the Preparatory Commission or working 
groups and expert groups. On 27 June, Mr Ian Kenyon, Executive 
Secretary of the Preparatory Commission, will present a report 
reviewing developments and issues since the sixth plenary 
session in mid-April. Questions to be examined include the 
organisations' budget and programme, training of inspectors, 
confidentiality policy, inspection procedures for chemical 
weapons facilities including equipment and sampling and so on. 
The new president for the period August 1994 to February 1995 
will be elected from one of the Latin American signatory states. 
The Convention on Chemical Weapons prohibits all development, 
production, acquisition, retention, stockpiling, transfer and 
use of chemical weapons. Signatory states are obliged to 
destroy their chemical weapons and chemical weapons production 
facilities as well as any chemical weapons they may have 
abandoned on another state's territory. Implementation of the 
convention will be verified through reporting requirements, 
on-site inspections and short-notice challenge inspections. The 
civilian chemical industry will also have to comply with 
obligations regarding the production, processing or consumption 
of chemicals that are considered relevant to the objectives of 
the convention. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

