<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK Dissociates Dehaene Candidacy From Greek Presidency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK Dissociates Dehaene Candidacy From Greek Presidency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2806122994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2806122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The British ambassador in Athens conveyed a verbal 
message to the Greek Government stressing that his country's 
refusal to accept Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene's 
candidacy for the European Union [EU] Commission presidency is 
not in any way related to the Greek presidency. The British 
message further stressed that there will be no deviation from 
this position, even at the extraordinary EU summit that will be 
held on 15 July in Brussels. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos made a statement on 
the issue today and told correspondents that Prime Minister 
Andreas Papandreou will assess the prerequisites for our 
country's representation at the extraordinary EU summit. It is 
recalled that the prime minister said in Corfu that our country 
will be represented at that summit at a lower level. 
  At the same time, commenting on press reports that the 
British prime minister, speaking in the House of Commons, 
attributed responsibility for the failure to elect a EU 
Commission president to the Greek Presidency, Mr. Venizelos 
expressed his regret and said that if this stands it is an 
isolated remark that is at odds with the impression of all the 
other EU members. 

</TEXT>

