<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Signs Draft IAEA Accord, Agrees to Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukraine Signs Draft IAEA Accord, Agrees to Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2906110794 Paris AFP in English 0957 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2906110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, June 29 (AFP) -- Ukraine has signed a draft 
agreement with the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] to 
allow the UN atomic watchdog agency to inspect its nuclear 
installations, an IAEA statement said Wednesday [29 June]. 
  Under the preliminary accord, "Ukraine undertakes to use the 
nuclear material and facilties under its jurisdiction or control 
exclusively for peaceful purposes." 
  The draft safeguards agreement, as it is known, was reached 
in two days of talks with Kiev officials at IAEA headquarters 
here and must be approved by the agency's Board of Governors 
takes it up in September. 
  It also provides for "the application of safeguards by the 
IAEA to all nuclear material in all peaceful nuclear activities 
of Ukraine." 
  IAEA spokesman Hans Friedrich Meyer said the draft accord is 
a key first step towards Ukraine's joining the Nuclear 
Non-proliferation Treaty. 
  Ukraine is the site of the world's worst civilian nuclear 
disaster, caused by a meltdown in the number four reactor at its 
Chernobyl nuclear plant on April 26, 1986. 
  Western states have been applying pressure for the plant to 
be totally shut down but President Leonid Kravchuk has brushed 
the demands aside, saying his country needs to keep it going for 
at least several more years to cover Ukraine's energy shortage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

