<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vranitzky: Isolation No Solution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vranitzky: Isolation No Solution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2806123294 Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network in German 
1000 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2806123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Gisela Hopfmueller] </F>
  [Excerpt] Following today's cabinet meeting, Chancellor 
Franz Vranitzky was asked his opinion about Vice Chancellor 
Busek's decision to boycott the upcoming visit by Chinese 
Premier Li Peng. 
  [Begin Vranitzky recording] I think there are only two 
options: Either you maintain contact with political 
representatives of a country like China, or you do not. And 
then you have to consider what you will achieve with these two 
options. I think that in spite of rejecting and condemning the 
human rights situation in China, we Austrians, and other 
Europeans as well, would not change the situation if we chose to 
isolate the country. It has become clear from several other 
cases where the human rights situation is also unsatisfactory 
that the willingness to meet, to cooperate, is the better 
possibility, the better solution than isolating the country 
concerned. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

