<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   OeVP, Greens Protest Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OeVP, Greens Protest Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2806132894 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 28 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> AU2806132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "a.s.": "China's Premier Li Peng To Visit </F>
Vienna -- Protests, While Industry Is Hoping"] 
  [Excerpts] Vienna -- The visit by Chinese Premier Li Peng, 
starting on Wednesday [29 June], is meeting with increasing 
protests in Austria that seem to be having some effect: Li Peng 
has canceled a severely criticized visit to Vienna's town hall 
and the signing of the Golden Book owing to his "tight 
schedule." Greens Spokesman Peter Pilz, and also the Viennese 
organization of the Austrian People's Party [OeVP] headed by 
Bernhard Goerg, had protested the planned signing of the Golden 
Book, announcing that they would boycott this act. 
  The Liberal Forum considers contact necessary, but says that 
"especially polite gestures" are inappropriate for the one 
responsible for the massacre in Tiananmen Square. Pilz called 
the guest a "mass murderer of the worst kind." 
  Several human rights organizations have announced that they 
will hold vigils and demonstrations. A vigil in front of the 
Federal Chancellery has, however, been banned by the 
authorities. [passage omitted] 
  Austria's industry is confident that Li Peng's five-day 
visit 
will result in orders from China. Besides ministers and state 
secretaries, the 270-strong delegation accompanying Li Peng will 
include 150 businessmen. Prior to the visit, the Chinese said 
that there is great demand for hydraulic power (turbines) and an 
interest in steel and railroad systems. A railroad agreement is 
to be signed. In addition to Vienna, the Chinese delegation 
will visit Linz (the nationalized Voest Alpine works) and 
Salzburg. 
  According to the Chinese Embassy, trade with China increased 
from 1.5 billion schillings in 1980 to 11.5 billion last year 
(imports: 7.8 billion). 
  The return visit to Chancellor Vranitzky's trip to China is 
the first visit to Austria by a Chinese premier. 

</TEXT>

