<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Advises Early Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Advises Early Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2306190794 Paris AFP in English 1847 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2306190794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 23 (AFP) -- France called for political 
dialogue in Algeria and elections as soon as possible, as 
Algerian Prime Minister Mokdad Sifi held a second day of talks 
with French officials on Thursday [23 June]. 
  Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said France considered a 
political dialogue with "all those who agree to put their knives 
and Kalashnikovs on one side" was "indispensable". 
  Speaking after a meeting with Sifi, Juppe said France hoped 
the dialogue would culminate in legislative elections "at the 
earliest possible date." [passage omitted] 
  On Thursday, Juppe said political stabilisation in Algeria 
would depend on the success of its economic recovery programme, 
notably in improving housing and cutting unemployment. [passage 
omitted] 
  Sifi also met with National Assembly speaker Philippe Seguin 
on Thursday. 

</TEXT>

