<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Giscard Comments on Rwanda Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Giscard Comments on Rwanda Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406162094 Paris Europe No. 1 Radio in French 0540 GMT 24 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2406162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Europe No. 1 Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Studio interview with Valery Giscard d'Estaing, president </F>
of the French Democratic Union, by Franz-Olivier Giesbert -- 
live] 
  [Excerpts] [Giesbert] Now a word about Rwanda and the 
French operation or this humanitarian invasion, as Info Matin 
calls it -- is it a good thing? 
  [Giscard] [passage omitted] I think we have to look very 
carefully at this operation, which poses problems, because it is 
not a United Nations action, it is a national action being 
carried out by France. [passage omitted] Our mission is thus in 
fact a humanitarian mission, but one which must be temporary and 
extremely cautious, because Africa has responsibility for the 
situation, not Europe, much less France. [passage omitted] 
  It is a mission which has a chance only if it is strictly 
humanitarian and above all temporary, and its objective is to 
wait for the planned arrival of UN forces, which may arrive 
late. So, you see, it is an operation which must be carried out 
very carefully. The French forces must remain close to the 
border and must not penetrate into the interior of the country. 
Their mission is to protect groups of men, women, and clergy 
against the threat of massacre. It is not to take part in the 
fighting inside Rwanda. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

