<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Mate Granic Begins Official Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Croatia's Mate Granic Begins Official Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Foreign Minister Solana </H4>

<F P=102> LD2806192794 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
foreign minister, has started his official visit to Spain with 
an audience with King Juan Carlos. Elizabeta Gojan reports from 
Madrid. 
  [Gojan] [passage omitted] Spain's interest in the peaceful 
reintegration of the occupied Croatian regions, the situation in 
the area, Croatia's contribution to the ending of the war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, the aid extended by the European Union and 
Spain to the concrete implementation of the agreement on the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation -- these subjects were discussed 
this afternoon by Minister Granic and Javier Solana Madariaga, 
his Spanish counterpart. 
  [Begin recording] [Solana, in Spanish with superimposed 
Serbo-Croatian translation] As far as the Croatian regions 
under Serb occupation are concerned, the Spanish side will meet 
again this summer with high-ranking Croatian officials. 
  We wish to agree on influencing a possible renewal of the 
mandate of UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] before the autumn 
session of the UN General Assembly. 
  Spanish-Croatian relations have significantly improved, 
although they were not all that good in the past. 
  [Granic] Despite the Zagreb cease-fire agreement, there have 
been no further negotiations with the Serbs. On the contrary -- 
the UNPA's [UN Protected Areas] are being practically integrated 
into Serbia economically. Croatia refuses to accept this. 
Croatia will try -- in a peaceful and diplomatic way -- to 
resolve the issue of the reintegration of our occupied regions 
by requesting the help of the European Union and the UN General 
Assembly and Security Council. 
  As far as Bosnia-Herzegovina is concerned, Croatia upholds 
the Washington agreement and the Bosnian-Croat Federation -- 
including the future confederation between the Muslim-Croat 
Federation and the Republic of Croatia -- as well as the Contact 
Group's efforts aimed at finding a peaceful solution. [end 
recording] 
  [Gojan] The two ministers signed the first agreements 
between 
their two countries on road traffic and cooperation in the area 
of tourism. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

