<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Rejects Divisions Caused by Democracy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demirel Rejects Divisions Caused by Democracy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806162094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1540 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2806162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, June 28 (A.A) -- President Suleyman 
Demirel on Tuesday [28 June] said that if the West sees 
democracy in Turkey as allowing the country to split apart, 
Turkey will not be a part of it, adding terror in Turkey aims at 
dividing and attacking its unity. 
  Speaking at a conference at the military academy, he said 
that Turkey has a free press, elections and judgment. 
  He said there are people from different origins in Turkey 
who 
live together in peace, adding the Turkish people of Kurdish 
origin have been living here in peace for the last 1000 years. 
  "All have equal rights and all are first class citizen," he 
said. 
  Demirel also said that the southeastern region is part of 
Turkey and the indivisible unity of Turkey will always be 
protected by its people, organizations, and its armed forces. 
  He said that Turkey is facing problems but they will be 
overcome in time, adding the population increase must be taken 
down to 1 percent from the present 3 by the beginning of the 
next centruy and the agricultural population percentage must be 
lowered from its present 45 percent to 10 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-44336 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu125_q_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-125 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Speaker Comments on DEP Deputies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Speaker Comments on DEP Deputies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2406071194 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
0600 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2406071194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Husamettin Cindoruk, speaker of the Turkish Grand 
National Assembly [TGNA], has said that he is not contradicting 
the judiciary in connection with the Democracy Party [DEP] 
deputies, but merely following the Constitution. Cindoruk was 
replying to questions from reporters at Amsterdam airport, where 
he stopped off on his way to The Hague to attend the European 
parliamentary speakers conference. 
  The TGNA speaker pointed out that Turkey has legal ways to 
strip people of their parliamentary memberships. If there is a 
contradiction, he said, it can be set right through an appeal 
and judgment. Cindoruk stressed that the TGNA respects and is 
loyal to the Constitution and the law. 
  Replying to a question on attempts by the deputies who are 
abroad to gain the status of exiles, the TGNA speaker said that 
Turkish law and justice must be trusted. We want all our 
citizens to be in Turkey, he said, and we want these deputies to 
come to Turkey to pursue their rights. Cindoruk pointed out 
that one cannot sit abroad and demand that an injustice -- if 
one exists -- be righted. He said: If they are right, why 
should they live abroad with crimes attributed to them? 
Cindoruk stressed that Turkey has the mechanisms of parliament 
and public opinion to prevent the passage of unjust decisions. 
  Replying to a question on relations between the DEP and the 
PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] terror organization, Cindoruk 
said that while trying to crush an antidemocratic gang of 
bandits, Turkey exercises its sovereign rights within the 
framework of democratic rules. He stressed that nobody can 
defend a gang that kills innocent people or those who support 
that gang. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

