<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller To Offer Russia Exports for More Oil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciller To Offer Russia Exports for More Oil </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806163894 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1534 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2806163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 28 (A.A) -- The prime minister's 
adviser Volkan Vural on Tuesday [28 June] said that a long-term 
agreement with Russia aims at increasing Turkey's oil imports 
from that country to 3 million tonnes in return for export 
products and services to Russia from Turkey. 
  He said that presently Turkey buys one or two million tonnes 
of Russian oil as spot purchases and this could be expanded to 
three million tonnes, therefore entering a long-term agreement. 
  Vural said the oil deal would be discussed when Russian 
First 
Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets visits Turkey next month to 
consider how to increase trade and economic links. 
  `We would like to expand our exports of consumer goods to 
Russia, and we have a key interest in our investments in 
contracting and services there,' Vural said. 
  Turkey, which imports the bulk of its oil from Saudi Arabia 
and Iran, did not buy any Russian crude in the first quarter of 
this year, but took 129,000 tonnes in the same 1993 period. 

</TEXT>

