<H3> <TI>   Italy's Berlusconi `Satisfied' With Corfu Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Italy's Berlusconi `Satisfied' With Corfu Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2706102594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1135 GMT 25 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2706102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Martino Going to Bosnia, Berlusconi </F>
Pleased With Events"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Corfu, June 25 -- [passage omitted] In 
another development in Corfu today, where the EC summit is 
drawing to a close, Italian Premier Silvio Berlusconi said, "We 
are working very well to build relations with everyone," with 
reference to his and [Foreign Minister] Martino's first outing 
with the other European leaders. He said he was satisfied with 
the way the new Italian government has joined the complex 
dialogue at the summit level. 
  He reported that he and his foreign minister are fielding 
many questions on Italian positions on various issues and added, 
"The weight of the Italian delegation is expressed in the 
substance of the interventions." In this connection, he said 
Martino's remarks were on joblessness were "enlightening." 
  Talking to newspersons last night, Berlusconi managed to 
make 
a joke out of the misgiving expressed in the recent past by the 
Greek foreign minister, Theodhoros Pangalos, who cast doubt on 
the "democratic legitimacy" of the Italian government because of 
the presence in the cabinet of National Alliance ministers. 
  "He's always close, he doesn't leave me for a minute," said 
the Italian premier who also affirmed that he found Pangalos 
"very likable." "And then, he speaks excellent Italian," he 
added. 

</TEXT>

