<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK Creates `Extremely Awkward Situation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK Creates `Extremely Awkward Situation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2506145294 Hamburg DPA in German 1251 GMT 25 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2506145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Corfu (DPA) -- With only a few days before the 
German presidency of the EU [European Union] Council begins, 
Britain has thrown the EU into a new crisis and maneuvered the 
Federal Government into an extremely awkward situation. At the 
EU summit on Corfu on Saturday [25 June], in the controversy 
over nominating a new EU Commission president, British Prime 
Minister John Major defied all other EU partners and vetoed the 
designation of Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene. 
  Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who has been particularly 
committed to the nomination of Dehaene, is now forced to settle 
the dispute on the succession to current President Jacques 
Delors at a special summit in Brussels on 15 July. "As far as 
the chances of success are concerned, I cannot say anything 
right now," Kohl said at the conclusion of the Corfu summit. He 
would have much rather announced a decision "than having this 
problem now dumped in front of our front door." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

